By Dambisa Moyo
President Joe Biden’s speech last week to the United Nations General Assembly was notable for its strikingly hawkish tone toward China, with his warning that the United States was engaged in a new cold war with Beijing and the urgent need for America to respond to the challenge of authoritarianism. Biden’s speech also highlighted the deep and persistent differences between the United States and China, which have not been resolved in a post–Cold War world.
Biden’s cold war language also has implications for Africa, where China has rapidly grown its influence and engagement over the past decade. The current U.S.-China competition is also one of two primary fault lines in global politics—the other being Russia’s ambitions to reassert itself on its periphery—and it is likely to intensify in the coming years. At the same time, Africa continues to be increasingly targeted by foreign powers seeking influence and resources. The U.S.-China competition may provide some short-term opportunities for African countries but will likely exacerbate existing tensions and risks if handled poorly.
One of the challenges for policymakers is that this competition will not unfold as neatly as it might seem at first glance. The United States and China are unlikely to engage in a full-scale Cold War–style conflict or even a low-intensity one like that of the Korean War of 1950–53 or Vietnam War of 1965–75. However, this oversimplifies the nature of Beijing’s engagement in Africa and makes assumptions about its intentions that are unlikely to be borne out over time.
